class Sidebar(Gtk.Widget, Gtk.Accessible, Gtk.Buildable, Gtk.ConstraintTarget):
    """
    Adaptive sidebar widget.

    <picture>
      <source srcset="sidebar-dark.png" media="(prefers-color-scheme: dark)">
      <img src="sidebar.png" alt="sidebar">
    </picture>

    :class:`Adw.Sidebar` contains :class:`SidebarSection` objects, which in turn contain
    :class:`SidebarItem` objects.

    To add sections, use :meth:`Sidebar.append`, :meth:`Sidebar.prepend` or
    :meth:`Sidebar.insert`.

    To remove sections, use :meth:`Sidebar.remove` or
    :meth:`Sidebar.remove_all`.

    To inspect the items, use :meth:`Sidebar.get_item` or
    :attr:`Sidebar.items`.

    To inspect sections themselves, use :meth:`Sidebar.get_section` or
    :attr:`Sidebar.sections`.

    ## Selection and activation

    :class:`Adw.Sidebar` has zero or one selected items. The index of the item can be
    accessed and changed via :attr:`Sidebar.selected`. Set it to
    :data:`Gtk.INVALID_LIST_POSITION` to remove selection.

    Selection cannot be permanently disabled.

    :attr:`Sidebar.selected-item` can be used to access the selected item.

    Connect to the ``Sidebar::activated`` signal to run code when an item
    has been activated. This can be used to toggle the visible pane when used in
    a split view.

    See also: :class:`ViewSwitcherSidebar`.

    ## Modes

    <picture>
      <source srcset="sidebar-modes-dark.png" media="(prefers-color-scheme: dark)">
      <img src="sidebar-modes.png" alt="sidebar-modes">
    </picture>

    :class:`Adw.Sidebar` is adaptive and can act as either a regular sidebar, or a page
    of boxed lists.

    Use the :attr:`Sidebar.mode` to determine its look and behavior.

    A typical use case involves using :class:`Adw.Sidebar` inside the sidebar pane of a
    :class:`NavigationSplitView`, and switching mode to page whenever it's
    collapsed, as follows:

    .. code-block:: xml

        <object class=":class:`Adw.Window`">
          <property name="default-width">800</property>
          <property name="default-height">600</property>
          <child>
            <object class=":class:`Adw.Breakpoint`">
              <condition>max-width: 400sp</condition>
              <setter object="split_view" property="collapsed">True</setter>
              <setter object="sidebar" property="mode">page</setter>
            </object>
          </child>
          <property name="content">
            <object class=":class:`Adw.NavigationSplitView`" id="split_view">
              <property name="sidebar">
                <object class=":class:`Adw.NavigationPage`">
                  <property name="title" translatable="yes">Sidebar</property>
                  <property name="child">
                    <object class=":class:`Adw.ToolbarView`">
                      <child type="top">
                        <object class=":class:`Adw.HeaderBar`"/>
                      </child>
                      <property name="content">
                        <object class=":class:`Adw.Sidebar`" id="sidebar">
                          <!-- Calls :meth:`Adw.NavigationSplitView.set_show_content` (split_view, TRUE); -->
                          <signal name="activated" handler="sidebar_activated_cb"/>
                          <!-- ... -->
                        </object>
                      </property>
                    </object>
                  </property>
                </object>
              </property>
              <property name="content">
                <object class=":class:`Adw.NavigationPage`">
                  <property name="title" translatable="yes">Content</property>
                  <property name="child">
                    <!-- ... -->
                  </property>
                </object>
              </property>
            </object>
          </property>
        </object>

    When used with :class:`OverlaySplitView`, the sidebar should stay in sidebar
    mode, as the sidebar pane is still a sidebar when collapsed.

    ## Search

    :class:`Adw.Sidebar` supports filtering items via the :attr:`Sidebar.filter`
    property.

    Use :attr:`Sidebar.placeholder` to provide an empty state widget. It will
    be shown when all items have been filtered out, or the sidebar has no items
    otherwise.

    ## Context Menu

    To create a context menu for the sidebar items, use the
    :attr:`Sidebar.menu-model` property to provide a menu model, and the
    ``Sidebar::setup-menu`` signal to set up actions for the given item.

    To set or override the menu for just one section, use
    :attr:`SidebarSection.menu-model` instead.

    ## Drag-and-Drop

    :class:`Adw.Sidebar` items can have a drop target for arbitrary content.

    Use :meth:`Sidebar.setup_drop_target` to set it up, specifying the
    supported content types and drag actions, then connect to
    ``Sidebar::drop`` to handle drops.

    In some cases, it may be necessary to determine the used action based on the
    dragged content, or the hovered item.

    To determine it based on the sidebar item, connect to the
    ``Sidebar::drop-enter`` signal and return the action from its handler.

    To determine it based on the content, set :attr:`Sidebar.drop-preload` to
    ``True``, then connect to ``Sidebar::drop-value-loaded`` signal and return
    the action from its handler.

    In both cases the action will be passed as a parameter to the
    ``Sidebar::drop`` signal.

    Regardless of whether a drop target was set up, dragging content over sidebar
    items activates them after a timeout. To disable this behavior for specific
    items, set :attr:`SidebarItem.drag-motion-activate` to ``False`` on them.

    ## :class:`Adw.Sidebar` as ``GtkBuildable``

    :class:`Adw.Sidebar` allows adding sections as children.

    Example of an :class:`Adw.Sidebar` UI definition:

    .. code-block:: xml

        <object class=":class:`Adw.Sidebar`">
          <child>
            <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarSection`">
              <child>
                <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarItem`">
                  <property name="title" translatable="yes">Recent</property>
                  <property name="icon-name">document-open-recent-symbolic</property>
                </object>
              </child>
              <child>
                <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarItem`">
                  <property name="title" translatable="yes">Starred</property>
                  <property name="icon-name">starred-symbolic</property>
                </object>
              </child>
            </object>
          </child>
          <child>
            <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarSection`">
              <property name="title" translatable="yes">Places</property>
              <child>
                <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarItem`">
                  <property name="title" translatable="yes">Music</property>
                  <property name="icon-name">folder-music-symbolic</property>
                </object>
              </child>
              <child>
                <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarItem`">
                  <property name="title" translatable="yes">Pictures</property>
                  <property name="icon-name">folder-pictures-symbolic</property>
                </object>
              </child>
              <child>
                <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarItem`">
                  <property name="title" translatable="yes">Videos</property>
                  <property name="icon-name">folder-videos-symbolic</property>
                </object>
              </child>
            </object>
          </child>
          <child>
            <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarSection`">
              <child>
                <object class=":class:`Adw.SidebarItem`">
                  <property name="title" translatable="yes">Trash</property>
                  <property name="icon-name">user-trash-symbolic</property>
                </object>
              </child>
            </object>
          </child>
        </object>

    ## CSS nodes

    :class:`Adw.Sidebar` has a main CSS node with the name ``sidebar``.

    Internally, it's using a :class:`Gtk.ListBox` with the
    [``.navigation-sidebar``](style-classes.html#sidebars) style class in sidebar
    mode, or an :class:`PreferencesPage` in page mode.

    ## Accessibility

    :class:`Adw.Sidebar` uses the :class:`Gtk.AccessibleRole.generic` role.
    """
    gimeta: ClassVar[_GIMeta]
    drop_preload: bool
    filter: Gtk.Filter
    items: Gtk.SelectionModel
    menu_model: Gio.MenuModel
    mode: SidebarMode | int
    placeholder: Gtk.Widget
    sections: Gio.ListModel
    selected: int
    selected_item: SidebarItem
    def __init__(self, *, drop_preload: bool = ..., filter: Gtk.Filter = ..., menu_model: Gio.MenuModel = ..., mode: SidebarMode | int = ..., placeholder: Gtk.Widget = ..., selected: int = ..., **kwargs: Any) -> None: ...
    @classmethod
    def new(cls, *args: Any, **kwargs: Any) -> Self: ...
    def append(self, section: SidebarSection) -> None:
        """
        Appends ``section`` to ``self``.
        """
    def get_drop_preload(self) -> bool:
        """
        Gets whether drop data should be preloaded on hover.
        """
    def get_filter(self) -> Gtk.Filter | None:
        """
