    titlebar area. Instead, :class:`ToolbarView` can be used together with
    :class:`HeaderBar` or :class:`Gtk.HeaderBar` as follows:

    .. code-block:: xml

        <object class=":class:`Adw.Window`">
          <property name="content">
            <object class=":class:`Adw.ToolbarView`">
              <child type="top">
                <object class=":class:`Adw.HeaderBar`"/>
              </child>
              <property name="content">
                <!-- ... -->
              </property>
            </object>
          </property>
        </object>

    Using :attr:`Gtk.Window.titlebar` or :attr:`Gtk.Window.child`
    is not supported and will result in a crash. Use :attr:`Window.content`
    instead.

    ## Dialogs

    :class:`Adw.Window` can contain :class:`Dialog`. Use :meth:`Dialog.present` with the
    window or a widget within a window to show a dialog.

    ## Breakpoints

    :class:`Adw.Window` can be used with :class:`Breakpoint` the same way as
    :class:`BreakpointBin`. Refer to that widget's documentation for details.

    Example:

    .. code-block:: xml

        <object class=":class:`Adw.Window`">
          <property name="content">
            <object class=":class:`Adw.ToolbarView`">
              <child type="top">
                <object class=":class:`Adw.HeaderBar`"/>
              </child>
              <property name="content">
                <!-- ... -->
              </property>
              <child type="bottom">
                <object class="GtkActionBar" id="bottom_bar">
                  <property name="revealed">True</property>
                  <property name="visible">False</property>
                </object>
              </child>
            </object>
          </property>
          <child>
            <object class=":class:`Adw.Breakpoint`">
              <condition>max-width: 500px</condition>
              <setter object="bottom_bar" property="visible">True</setter>
            </object>
          </child>
